content.description:
Documented pitfalls discovered during Hobson development. Each was a real bug that cost debugging time.

## The parseInt Zero Trap

**Problem:** `parseInt("0px") || fallback` treats 0 as falsy.

```javascript
// WRONG ‚Äî window at x=0 jumps to fallback position
const x = parseInt(wrapper.style.left) || 50;

// CORRECT ‚Äî 0 is a valid position
const leftPx = parseInt(wrapper.style.left);
const x = isNaN(leftPx) ? 50 : leftPx;
```

**Why this matters:** Window position (0, 0) is valid. The `||` operator treats `0` as falsy, triggering the fallback. The `isNaN()` check correctly detects only parse failures.

**Pattern to use everywhere:**
```javascript
const parsed = parseInt(string);
const value = isNaN(parsed) ? defaultValue : parsed;
```

## Backward Compatibility: String ‚Üí Object Attachments

Attachments evolved from string arrays to positioned objects:

```javascript
// Old format
attachments: ["item-1", "item-2"]

// Current format
attachments: [{ id: "item-1", view: { type: "...", x: 20, y: 20, ... } }]
```

All code that reads attachments must handle both:

```javascript
const childId = typeof child === 'string' ? child : child.id;
```

String-format attachments convert to object format on first interaction.

## Reading Position from DOM, Not Closures

When starting a drag, read the current position from the DOM element ‚Äî not from the render-time closure:

```javascript
// WRONG ‚Äî uses stale render-time data
const startLeft = child.x;

// CORRECT ‚Äî reads actual current DOM position
const leftPx = parseInt(wrapper.style.left);
const startLeft = isNaN(leftPx) ? child.x : leftPx;
```

See [Stale Closure Prevention](item://c0c0c0c0-0011-0000-0000-000000000000) for the full pattern.

## Updating Multiple Properties Together

When modifying item data, include all properties ‚Äî not just the one you're changing:

```javascript
// WRONG ‚Äî loses other properties when converting string to object
const updates = { x: newX, y: newY };

// CORRECT ‚Äî includes all properties for complete data
const updates = {
  x: newX, y: newY,
  width: width, height: height,
  z: currentZ
};
```

This is especially important when converting string-format attachments to object format.

## Global Listeners for Drag

Attach `mousemove` and `mouseup` listeners to `document`, not to the element being dragged:

```javascript
// WRONG ‚Äî loses drag if mouse leaves the element
titlebar.onmousemove = handleDrag;

// CORRECT ‚Äî captures drag everywhere
document.addEventListener('mousemove', handleDrag);
document.addEventListener('mouseup', handleDragEnd);
```

The mouse can leave the window during a drag. Titlebar-only listeners lose the interaction.

## setTimeout(0) for Post-Render Work

After replacing DOM content, use `setTimeout(..., 0)` to defer operations that depend on the new DOM being in place:

```javascript
mainView.appendChild(newContent);
setTimeout(() => {
  // Now the DOM is fully rendered and measurable
  restoreScrollPositions();
}, 0);
```

## Hob Atoms and Re-render Loops

**Problem:** A Hob view creates atoms during its tracked evaluation. When a click handler calls `(reset! my-atom new-val)`, the atom mutation callback triggers a full re-render of the same view, creating fresh atoms with default values ‚Äî wiping all state.

**Why it happens:** During `renderHobView`, `startTracking()` is active. `(deref my-atom)` inside build functions calls `recordAtomAccess(atom)`, registering the atom as a dependency. Later, `(reset! my-atom ...)` fires `_atomMutationCallback` ‚Üí rendering system finds dependents ‚Üí schedules re-render ‚Üí entire Hob code re-evaluated with fresh atoms.

**The fix (platform-level):** Atoms are tagged with `_ownerCtx` (the tracking context ID active when they were created). `recordAtomAccess` skips self-owned atoms ‚Äî atoms created by a view's own evaluation don't become dependencies of that view. This means `reset!` on view-local atoms drives local updates via `dom-set-content!` without triggering re-renders.

**Symptoms if broken:** Click handlers produce a brief DOM flash then revert. State appears to reset after every interaction. Console may show `[Reactivity] Cycle detected`.

## Hob‚ÜîJS Interop: Async Callbacks

**Problem:** Hob functions are always async (return Promises). Passing a Hob function to a JS API that expects a synchronous callback produces subtle bugs.

```hob
;; WRONG ‚Äî Array.find calls the callback synchronously.
;; The Hob fn returns a Promise (always truthy), so find matches the first element.
(invoke my-array "find" (fn [c] (= (:id c) target-id)))

;; CORRECT ‚Äî use Hob-native filter + first
(first (filter (fn [c] (= (:id c) target-id)) my-array))
```

Other affected JS APIs: `Array.sort`, `Array.every`, `Array.some`, any JS library that expects synchronous callbacks for return values.

**Pattern:** If a JS API needs a synchronous callback that returns a value, pre-compute the result in Hob (where async is handled naturally) and pass the result directly, or use Hob-native equivalents.

## Hob invoke Argument Order

**Problem:** `invoke` calls `obj[method](...args)`. A common mistake is to extract the method first and then try to call it.

```hob
;; WRONG ‚Äî does parseInt[value]() which is nonsensical
(invoke (dom-get win :parseInt) value)

;; CORRECT ‚Äî calls window.parseInt(value)
(invoke win "parseInt" value)
```

## data-sort-key for Morphdom Matching

**Problem:** Morphdom matches elements by position when they lack identifying attributes. If a list re-renders with different items, morphdom patches element N with data from new element N ‚Äî reusing old event handlers with wrong data.

**Fix:** Always add `data-sort-key` to elements rendered in loops (window wrappers, minimized pills, list items). Morphdom uses `data-sort-key` or `id` for identity matching.

## See Also

- [Silent Update Pattern](item://c0c0c0c0-0010-0000-0000-000000000000) ‚Äî Context for many of these gotchas
- [Stale Closure Prevention](item://c0c0c0c0-0011-0000-0000-000000000000) ‚Äî The most common source of bugs
- [Rendering & Views](item://c0c0c0c0-0022-0000-0000-000000000000) ‚Äî Hob views and reactivity details
- [Spatial Windowing](item://ef793c27-2d4b-4c99-b05a-2769db5bc5a9) ‚Äî Where most of these were discovered
